{"title_page": "1975 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1975\n  |team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n  |sport=football\n  |image=\n  |image_size=\n  |conference=Ohio Valley Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=OVC\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=3\n  |record=11\u20132\n  |conf_record=6\u20131\n  |head_coach= [[Jimmy Feix]]\n  |hc_year=8th\n  |off_coach=\n  |def_coach=\n  |off_scheme=\n  |def_scheme=\n| captain = Rick Green\n| captain2 = Bob Hobby (alt.)\n  |stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium|L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n  |champion= OVC co-champion\n  |bowl= Camellia Bowl\n  |bowl_result= L 14\u201316 vs. [[1975 Northern Michigan Wildcats football team|Northern Michigan]]\n}}\n{{1975 Ohio Valley football standings}}\nThe '''1975 Western Kentucky football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] during the [[1975 NCAA Division II football season]]. The team came off an 7\u20133 record from the prior season<ref>http://college-football-results.com/f/wkentuck.htm</ref> and was led by coach [[Jimmy Feix]]. They claimed a share of the [[List of Ohio Valley Conference football champions|Ohio Valley Conference]] championship and returned to the [[NCAA Division II Football Championship]] for the second time in three years.  One of the highlights of the season was a victory over NCAA Division I [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]].<ref>[https://wkusports.com/sports/football/schedule/1975 1975 WKU Football schedule and results retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>  The Hilltoppers won their first two playoff games, including a win over [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire]] in the [[Grantland Rice Bowl]], before falling in the championship game to [[1975 Northern Michigan Wildcats football team|Northern Michigan]] in the [[Camellia Bowl (1961\u201380)|Camellia Bowl]].<ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/history/football/d2 NCAA Division 2 Football Championship History retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>   They finished ranked 3rd in both the AP and UPI final polls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Javelinas First in Final AP Poll|newspaper=Valley Morning Star|location=Harlingen, Texas|date=December 20, 1975|page=B3|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11329028/poll_1975_1220_ii_ap_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 28, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NCAA Division II UPI Final Poll|newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel|location=Orlando, Florida|date=November 26, 1975|page=2-C|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11328992/poll_1975_1126_ii_upi_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 28, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref><br><br>\n\nThis team was one of the best in school history and included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players Rick Caswell, David Carter, Darryl Drake, and Biff Madon.  Rick Green was named to the AP All American team as well as the OVC Defensive Player of the Year and Feix was named Divisional Kodak College Coach-of-the-Year.<ref>[https://www.wbko.com/content/news/Legendary-WKU-Coach-Feix-Named-To-College-Football-Hall-Of-Fame-Ballot-510919021.html Legendary WKU Coach Feix Named To College Football Hall Of Fame Ballot retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>  The All OVC team included Green, Sheroid Barrett, Chip Carpenter, Walt Herod, John Leathers, and Keith Tandy.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref><br><br>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rank = y\n| rankyear = 1973\n| poll = AP\n| attend = y\n| source = y\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division II football\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 6\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Dayton Flyers|title=Dayton}}\n| site_stadium = [[Welcome Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = Dayton, OH\n| score = 27\u20137\n| attend = 11,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 13\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1975 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]]\n| site_stadium = [[Old Cardinal Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = Louisville, KY\n| score = 21\u201317\n| attend = 34,700\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 20\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Illinois State Redbirds|title=Illinois State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium|L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n| score = 24-14\n| attend = 15,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 27\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Austin Peay Governors|title=Austin Peay}}\n| rank = 2\n| site_stadium = [[Governors Stadium|Municipal Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Clarksville, Tennessee]]\n| score = 30\u20133\n| attend = 6,800\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 4\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=East Tennessee State Buccaneers|title=East Tennessee State}}\n| rank = 2\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 17\u20130\n| attend = 14,400\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 18\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Tennessee Tech Golden Eagles|title=Tennessee Tech}}\n| rank = 2\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 20\u20137\n| attend = 9,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 25\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = No. 4 {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Eastern Kentucky Colonels|title=Eastern Kentucky}}\n| rank = 2\n| gamename = [[Battle of the Bluegrass]]\n| site_stadium = [[Hanger Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Richmond, Kentucky]]\n| score = 7\u201313\n| attend = 24,200\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 1\n| w/l = w\n| homecoming = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Morehead State Eagles|title=Morehead State}}\n| rank = 6\n| gamename = Homecoming\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 14\u201310\n| attend = 20,100\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 8\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders|title=Middle Tennessee}}\n| rank = 6\n| site_stadium = [[Johnny \"Red\" Floyd Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]]\n| score = 24\u201310\n| attend = 11,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 22\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Murray State Racers|title=Murray State}}\n| rank = 5\n| gamename = [[Battle for the Red Belt]]\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 19\u20130\n| attend = 15,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 29\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = No. 10 {{cfb link|year=1975|team=Northern Iowa Panthers|title=Northern Iowa}}\n| rank = 4\n| gamename = NCAA Quarterfinal\n| site_stadium = [[O. R. Latham Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Cedar Falls, Iowa]]\n| score = 14\u201312\n| attend = 2,500\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 6\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1975|team=New Hampshire Wildcats|title=New Hampshire}}\n| rank = 4\n| gamename = [[1975 Grantland Rice Bowl|Grantland Rice Bowl \u2013 NCAA Semifinal)]]\n| site_stadium = [[BREC Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n| score = 14\u20133\n| attend = 6,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 13\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = No. 5 [[1975 Northern Michigan Wildcats football team|Northern Michigan]]\n| rank = 4\n| gamename = [[1973 Camellia Bowl|Camellia Bowl \u2013 NCAA Championship)]]\n| site_stadium = [[Charles C. Hughes Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Sacramento, California]]\n| score = 14\u201316\n| attend = 15,558\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Ohio Valley Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1975 Ohio Valley Conference football season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:Ohio Valley Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1975 in sports in Kentucky|Western Kentucky]]\n\n\n{{collegefootball-1970s-season-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1975\n  |team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n  |sport=football\n  |image=\n  |image_size=\n  |conference=Ohio Valley Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=OVC\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=3\n  |record=11\u20132\n  |conf_record=6\u20131\n  |head_coach= [[Jimmy Feix]]\n  |hc_year=8th\n  |off_coach=\n  |def_coach=\n  |off_scheme=\n  |def_scheme=\n| captain = Rick Green\n| captain2 = Bob Hobby (alt.)\n  |stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium|L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n  |champion= OVC co-champion\n  |bowl= Camellia Bowl\n  |bowl_result= L 14\u201316 vs. [[1975 Northern Michigan Wildcats football team|Northern Michigan]]\n}}\n{{1975 Ohio Valley football standings}}\nThe '''1975 Western Kentucky football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] during the [[1975 NCAA Division II football season]]. The team came off an 7\u20133 record from the prior season<ref>http://college-football-results.com/f/wkentuck.htm</ref> and was led by coach [[Jimmy Feix]]. They claimed a share of the [[List of Ohio Valley Conference football champions|Ohio Valley Conference]] championship and returned to the [[NCAA Division II Football Championship]] for the second time in three years.  One of the highlights of the season was a victory over NCAA Division I [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]].<ref>[https://wkusports.com/sports/football/schedule/1975 1975 WKU Football schedule and results retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>  The Hilltoppers won their first two playoff games, including a win over [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire]] in the [[Grantland Rice Bowl]], before falling in the championship game to [[1975 Northern Michigan Wildcats football team|Northern Michigan]] in the [[Camellia Bowl (1961\u201380)|Camellia Bowl]].<ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/history/football/d2 NCAA Division 2 Football Championship History retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>   They finished ranked 3rd in both the AP and UPI final polls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Javelinas First in Final AP Poll|newspaper=Valley Morning Star|location=Harlingen, Texas|date=December 20, 1975|page=B3|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11329028/poll_1975_1220_ii_ap_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 28, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NCAA Division II UPI Final Poll|newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel|location=Orlando, Florida|date=November 26, 1975|page=2-C|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11328992/poll_1975_1126_ii_upi_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 28, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref><br><br>\n\nThis team was one of the best in school history and included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players Rick Caswell, David Carter, Darryl Drake, and Biff Madon.  Rick Green was named to the AP All American team as well as the OVC Defensive Player of the Year and Feix was named Divisional Kodak College Coach-of-the-Year.<ref>[https://www.wbko.com/content/news/Legendary-WKU-Coach-Feix-Named-To-College-Football-Hall-Of-Fame-Ballot-510919021.html Legendary WKU Coach Feix Named To College Football Hall Of Fame Ballot retrieved 2 April 2020.]</ref>  The All OVC team included Green, Sheroid Barrett, Chip Carpenter, Walt Herod, John Leathers, and Keith Tandy.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref><br><br>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rank = y\n| rankyear = 1973\n| poll = AP\n| attend = y\n| source = y\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division II football\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 6\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent