ers' Hall of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://llsjuponline.com/llsjup_online/Catalog/CatalogCourses.aspx?Year=2018&Semester=3&InstructorID=440&InstructorGroupID=0&SemesterAdd=0&InstructorShowAll=1&rememberRow=0&rememberCol=0|title=Gary Wiren, Ph.D. at FAU - Lifelong Learning Jupiter|website=llsjuponline.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas Michael Shanahan]], former [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Nebraska]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heafeyheafey.com/thomas-m-shanahan/|title=Thomas M. Shanahan|date=2017-01-09|website=Heafey Hoffmann Dworak Cutler|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[John Patrick Raynor]], Twentieth president of [[Marquette University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.anb.org/view/10.1093/anb/9780198606697.001.0001/anb-9780198606697-e-0802363|title=Raynor, John Patrick (1923-1997), educator, university president, and clergyman {{!}} American National Biography|website=anb.org|language=en|doi=10.1093/anb/9780198606697.001.0001/anb-9780198606697-e-0802363|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[Albert Gerard Schatz]], former [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Nebraska]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ned.uscourts.gov/internetDocs/judicialArchive/AGS_Memoriam.pdf|title=HONORABLE ALBERT G. SCHATZ|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.creightonprep.creighton.edu/}}\n* [https://jayjournal.org/ Jay Journal] - Student news site\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Omaha}}\n{{Jesuit Secondary Education Association}}\n\n[[Category:Jesuit high schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:High schools in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Omaha]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1878]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Nebraska]]\n", "name_user": "Etriusus", "label": "safe", "comment": "source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creighton_Preparatory_School"}
{"title_page": "Bice Osei Kuffour", "text_new": "'''Bice Osei Kuffour''' (born 17 November 1981) is a [[Ghana]]ian [[hiplife]] musician,<ref name=JOY>\n{{cite web|title=Obour is new MUSIGA President|url=http://lifestyle.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201108/71314.php|publisher=www.myjoyonline.com|accessdate=19 August 2011}}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> known popularly by the name '''Obour''', which means \"stone\" in the [[Akan language]]. He is the immediate past president of the [[Musicians Union of Ghana]] '''(MUSIGA)''',<ref name=JOY/><ref name=PRES>{{cite web|title=Obour Elected MUSIGA President|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/346020/1/obour-elected-musiga-president.html|publisher=www.modernghana.com|accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref> an [[umbrella group]] that unites all musicians in Ghana irrespective of genre.<ref>Selase Attah, [http://www.ghananie.com/?p=315 \"Pressure mounts on Obour as MUSIGA elections loom\"], Ghanaie.com, 12 June 2015.</ref> Obour is an alumnus of the [[University of Ghana]], the US International Visitor Leadership Programme, Aspen Global Leadership Network, and African Leadership Initiative of West Africa. He was the youngest recipient of the State Grand Medal Honour given by President J. A Kufuor in 2008. He is a social activist who doubles as a National Road Safety Ambassador;\nW.H.O Tuberculosis Ambassador\nBritish Council & Forest Commission of Ghana Climate Change Ambassador. \nHe is President and Founder of the Christiana Addo Memorial Foundation which promotes education, sanitation, personal hygiene and youth empowerment in Asante Akyem.\n\n\n==Life and career==\nObour was born at \"Braha Bebu Me\" (Dekyemenso) in the [[Ashanti Region]] on 7 November 1981, to Christiana Addo and Reverend B. O. Kuffour. At the age of six, Obour played many types of drums, especially the Atumpan, in the Juaso-Ashanti Akyem chief's palace where his father used to preside. Obour was educated at the State Experimental School ([[Kumasi]]), the Soul Clinic School ([[Accra]]), Garison Junior Secondary School ([[Burma Camp]]) and [[Mfantsipim School]] ([[Cape Coast]]).\n\nAfter finishing secondary school, Obour solicited help from his London-based cousin, J. Amano, who connected him with his personal Soul Records label. He subsequently released ''Atentenben'' which won three awards for Soul Records at the [[Ghana Music Awards]] in 2002, including Video of the year. This, and other songs by the label, led to Soul Records being awarded with Record Label of the Year. The same video won the Best at Our Music Awards (OMA) in 2002.\n\nHe was already a celebrity by the time he entered the [[University of Ghana]] in 2002 to study Sociology and Music, as a member of Commonwealth Hall (Vandal City).<ref>Mustapha Jimah, [http://www.modernghana.com/music/9063/3/congratulations-obour-you-deserve-it.html \"Congratulations Obour. You Deserve It\"], Modern Ghana, 23 April 2009.</ref><ref>Nii Ogbamey Tetteh, [http://www.ghanaforum.com/showthread.php/4010-I-am-the-first-hip-life-University-graduate \"'I am the first hip life University graduate'\"], Ghana Forum, 17 March 2011.</ref> His second album, entitled ''Dondo'', was led by the track \"Nana Obour\", which had earlier featured on Soul Records\u2032 ''Adakamo'' compilation album. ''Dondo'' also featured such classic tunes as \"Mesoodae\" and \"Palm Wine\". \"Nana Obour\" won the Best Video at both Ghana Music Awards and Ghana Music Awards UK in 2003.\n\nIn 2005, he established a pub in Osu and a music production company.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nObour has led several national campaigns because of his positive and educative lyrics. He won five awards at the 2005 Ghana Music Awards. His albums include ''Atentenben'', ''Akademua'', ''Dondo,Atumpan, President Obour and Fontomfrom''. He made a duet album with [[A. B. Crentsil]] entitled ''The Best of the Lifes''. Obour's 2004 album ''Obour.com''<ref>[http://www.modernghana.com/music/704/3/obour-to-launch-new-album.html \"Obour To Launch New Album\"], Modern Ghana, 2 June 2004.</ref> produced the hit single \"Konkontiba\".<ref>[http://www.modernghana.com/music/897/3/konkontiba-tops-musical-charts.html \"\u2018Konkontiba\u2019 Tops Musical Charts\"], Modern Ghana, 15 October 2004.</ref> He released a socially conscious album and project, ''One Ghana Peace Project/Obour for President'', ahead of the 2008 general elections. He went on to embark on a Nationwide Peace Campaign. Obour was selected among 12 other emerging leaders by The African Leadership Initiative to pursue training with the Aspen Global Leadership Network.\n\nHe is the immediate past President of the [[Musicians Union of Ghana]], the National TB Ambassador of Ghana,<ref>[http://stoptb.org/news/stories/2011/ns11_028.asp \"Musician Obour named as national TB ambassador for Ghana\"], Stop TB Partnership, 2011.</ref> Road Safety Ambassador, Executive icon of Youth Icons Africa and a Climate Change Champion for the [[British Council]]. He serves on several executive and advisory boards, including the executive committee of the International Federation of Musicians, University of Ghana School of Performing Arts advisory board, [[National Commission on Culture]], National Folklore board and the   [[Ghana Music Rights Organization|Ghana Music Rights Organisation]] board. \n\nIn 2017, Obour and his siblings established the Christiana Addo Memorial Foundation to help the people in the Asante Akyem South constituency of the Ashanti Region. He became more involved in the activities of the constituency as Chiefs and several youth groups called on him to consider representing them as their Member of Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-has-taken-a-quick-diversion-into-politics-780900|title=Obour has taken a quick diversion into politics|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n9.https://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-s-CAMF-grants-scholarships-to-students-696260\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aCZjl_inZz8 \"Obour, My Ghana Musician of the Decade\"], video interview.\n*https://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-s-CAMF-grants-scholarships-to-students-696260\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osei Kuffour, Bice Obour}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian musicians]]\n[[Category:University of Ghana alumni]]\n[[Category:Mfantsipim School alumni]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Bice Osei Kuffour''' (born 17 November 1981) is a [[Ghana]]ian [[hiplife]] musician,<ref name=JOY>\n{{cite web|title=Obour is new MUSIGA President|url=http://lifestyle.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201108/71314.php|publisher=www.myjoyonline.com|accessdate=19 August 2011}}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> known popularly by the name '''Obour''', which means \"stone\" in the [[Akan language]]. He is the immediate past president of the [[Musicians Union of Ghana]] (MUSIGA),<ref name=JOY/><ref name=PRES>{{cite web|title=Obour Elected MUSIGA President|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/346020/1/obour-elected-musiga-president.html|publisher=www.modernghana.com|accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref> an [[umbrella group]] that unites all musicians in Ghana irrespective of genre.<ref>Selase Attah, [http://www.ghananie.com/?p=315 \"Pressure mounts on Obour as MUSIGA elections loom\"], Ghanaie.com, 12 June 2015.</ref> Obour is an alumnus of the [[University of Ghana]], the US International Visitor Leadership Programme, Aspen Global Leadership Network, and African Leadership Initiative of West Africa. He was the youngest recipient of the State Grand Medal Honour given by President J. A Kufuor in 2008. He is a social activist who doubles as a National Road Safety Ambassador;\nW.H.O Tuberculosis Ambassador\nBritish Council & Forest Commission of Ghana Climate Change Ambassador. \nHe is President and Founder of the Christiana Addo Memorial Foundation which promotes education, sanitation, personal hygiene and youth empowerment in Asante Akyem.\n\n\n==Life and career==\nObour was born at \"Braha Bebu Me\" (Dekyemenso) in the [[Ashanti Region]] on 7 November 1981, to Christiana Addo and Reverend B. O. Kuffour. At the age of six, Obour played many types of drums, especially the Atumpan, in the Juaso-Ashanti Akyem chief's palace where his father used to preside. Obour was educated at the State Experimental School ([[Kumasi]]), the Soul Clinic School ([[Accra]]), Garison Junior Secondary School ([[Burma Camp]]) and [[Mfantsipim School]] ([[Cape Coast]]).\n\nAfter finishing secondary school, Obour solicited help from his London-based cousin, J. Amano, who connected him with his personal Soul Records label. He subsequently released ''Atentenben'' which won three awards for Soul Records at the [[Ghana Music Awards]] in 2002, including Video of the year. This, and other songs by the label, led to Soul Records being awarded with Record Label of the Year. The same video won the Best at Our Music Awards (OMA) in 2002.\n\nHe was already a celebrity by the time he entered the [[University of Ghana]] in 2002 to study Sociology and Music, as a member of Commonwealth Hall (Vandal City).<ref>Mustapha Jimah, [http://www.modernghana.com/music/9063/3/congratulations-obour-you-deserve-it.html \"Congratulations Obour. You Deserve It\"], Modern Ghana, 23 April 2009.</ref><ref>Nii Ogbamey Tetteh, [http://www.ghanaforum.com/showthread.php/4010-I-am-the-first-hip-life-University-graduate \"'I am the first hip life University graduate'\"], Ghana Forum, 17 March 2011.</ref> His second album, entitled ''Dondo'', was led by the track \"Nana Obour\", which had earlier featured on Soul Records\u2032 ''Adakamo'' compilation album. ''Dondo'' also featured such classic tunes as \"Mesoodae\" and \"Palm Wine\". \"Nana Obour\" won the Best Video at both Ghana Music Awards and Ghana Music Awards UK in 2003.\n\nIn 2005, he established a pub in Osu and a music production company.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nObour has led several national campaigns because of his positive and educative lyrics. He won five awards at the 2005 Ghana Music Awards. His albums include ''Atentenben'', ''Akademua'', ''Dondo,Atumpan, President Obour and Fontomfrom''. He made a duet album with [[A. B. Crentsil]] entitled ''The Best of the Lifes''. Obour's 2004 album ''Obour.com''<ref>[http://www.modernghana.com/music/704/3/obour-to-launch-new-album.html \"Obour To Launch New Album\"], Modern Ghana, 2 June 2004.</ref> produced the hit single \"Konkontiba\".<ref>[http://www.modernghana.com/music/897/3/konkontiba-tops-musical-charts.html \"\u2018Konkontiba\u2019 Tops Musical Charts\"], Modern Ghana, 15 October 2004.</ref> He released a socially conscious album and project, ''One Ghana Peace Project/Obour for President'', ahead of the 2008 general elections. He went on to embark on a Nationwide Peace Campaign. Obour was selected among 12 other emerging leaders by The African Leadership Initiative to pursue training with the Aspen Global Leadership Network.\n\nHe is the immediate past President of the [[Musicians Union of Ghana]], the National TB Ambassador of Ghana,<ref>[http://stoptb.org/news/stories/2011/ns11_028.asp \"Musician Obour named as national TB ambassador for Ghana\"], Stop TB Partnership, 2011.</ref> Road Safety Ambassador, Executive icon of Youth Icons Africa and a Climate Change Champion for the [[British Council]]. He serves on several executive and advisory boards, including the executive committee of the International Federation of Musicians, University of Ghana School of Performing Arts advisory board, [[National Commission on Culture]], National Folklore board and the   [[Ghana Music Rights Organization|Ghana Music Rights Organisation]] board. \n\nIn 2017, Obour and his siblings established the Christiana Addo Memorial Foundation to help the people in the Asante Akyem South constituency of the Ashanti Region. He became more involved in the activities of the constituency as Chiefs and several youth groups called on him to consider representing them as their Member of Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-has-taken-a-quick-diversion-into-politics-780900|title=Obour has taken a quick diversion into politics|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n9.https://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-s-CAMF-grants-scholarships-to-students-696260\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aCZjl_inZz8 \"Obour, My Ghana Musician of the Decade\"], video interview.\n*https://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Obour-s-CAMF-grants-scholarships-to-students-696260\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osei Kuffour, Bice Obour}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian musicians]]\n[[Category:University of Ghana alumni]]\n[[Category:Mfantsipim School alumni]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "name_user": "Gkbediako", "label": "safe", "comment": "Gave MUSIGA bold lettering", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bice_Osei_Kuffour"}
{"title_page": "Sakawa", "text_new": "{{about|a Ghanaian phenomenon|the town in Japan|Sakawa, K\u014dchi}}\n\n'''Sakawa''' is a Ghanaian term for illegal practices which combine modern Internet-based fraud with African traditionalist rituals.The term or word Sakawa is an Hausa word which means ''putting inside''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161|title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters|last=Darko|first=Sammy|date=10 May 2015|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=4 March 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Darko|first=Sammy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161|title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters|date=2015-05-10|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>The rituals, which are mostly in the form of sacrifices, are intended to spiritually manipulate victims so that the scammer's fraud is successful.  The term Sakawa referred to specific online scams but has since broadened to include all types of [[419 scams|online frauds]] and scams mainly targeting foreigners. The scammers flaunt stylish clothes, luxury cars, and enormous wealth, in order to promote this act. In impoverished areas, it can be seen as a way of survival for some.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o26Eks801oc |title=Internet Scamming in Ghana |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Abubakar |first=Zulaihatu |url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/419261/1/sakawa-guy-confesses.html |title=Sakawa Guy Confesses |publisher=Modern Ghana |date=2012-09-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=260823 |title=Six teenagers engage in mysterious Sakawa deal &#124; General News 2012-12-30 |publisher=GhanaWeb |date=2012-12-30 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Akwetey-Okunor |first=Isaac |url=http://thechronicle.com.gh/sakawa-coffin-exhibited-in-public/ |title=Sakawa coffin exhibited in public &#124; Ghanaian Chronicle |publisher=The Ghanaian Chronicle |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic.com.gh/archive/features/the-sakawa-menace-any-solutions.html |title=The sakawa menace ...Any solutions &#124; features |publisher=Daily Graphic |last=Dzandu |first=Sammy |date=2013-06-03 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\nScammers involved in this practice call themselves Sakawa boys.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Darko |first1=Sammy |title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> A culture has developed around Sakawa which has influenced music and clothing brands. Movies depicting the lifestyle have become popular, a movement lead by Ghanaian filmaker [[Socrate Safo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Morton |title=The Sakawa Boys: Inside the Bizarre Criminal World of Ghana\u2019s Cyber-Juju Email Scam Gangs |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/4xx393/the-sakawa-boys-inside-the-bizarre-criminal-world-of-ghanas-cyber-juju-email-scam-gangs |website=Vice |language=en |date=5 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Crime in Ghana]]\n*[[Nigerian scam]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/4xx393/the-sakawa-boys-inside-the-bizarre-criminal-world-of-ghanas-cyber-juju-email-scam-gangs The Sakawa Boys], a documentary about the phenomenon.\n*[http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/off-topic/a-look-at-the-real-social-engineers/ A Look at the Real African Social Engineers], an article on Sakawa culture.\n*[http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/security-awareness/the-anatomy-of-a-scam/ The Anatomy Of a Sakawa Scam], an article detailing sakawa type frauds.\n\n[[Category:Crime in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Internet fraud]]\n[[Category:African witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Crimes involving Satanism or the occult]]\n\n{{ghana-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|a Ghanaian phenomenon|the town in Japan|Sakawa, K\u014dchi}}\n\n'''Sakawa''' is a Ghanaian term for illegal practices which combine modern Internet-based fraud with African traditionalist rituals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161|title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters|last=Darko|first=Sammy|date=10 May 2015|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=4 March 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The rituals, which are mostly in the form of sacrifices, are intended to spiritually manipulate victims so that the scammer's fraud is successful.  The term Sakawa referred to specific online scams but has since broadened to include all types of [[419 scams|online frauds]] and scams mainly targeting foreigners. The scammers flaunt stylish clothes, luxury cars, and enormous wealth, in order to promote this act. In impoverished areas, it can be seen as a way of survival for some.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o26Eks801oc |title=Internet Scamming in Ghana |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Abubakar |first=Zulaihatu |url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/419261/1/sakawa-guy-confesses.html |title=Sakawa Guy Confesses |publisher=Modern Ghana |date=2012-09-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=260823 |title=Six teenagers engage in mysterious Sakawa deal &#124; General News 2012-12-30 |publisher=GhanaWeb |date=2012-12-30 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Akwetey-Okunor |first=Isaac |url=http://thechronicle.com.gh/sakawa-coffin-exhibited-in-public/ |title=Sakawa coffin exhibited in public &#124; Ghanaian Chronicle |publisher=The Ghanaian Chronicle |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic.com.gh/archive/features/the-sakawa-menace-any-solutions.html |title=The sakawa menace ...Any solutions &#124; features |publisher=Daily Graphic |last=Dzandu |first=Sammy |date=2013-06-03 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\nScammers involved in this practice call themselves Sakawa boys.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Darko |first1=Sammy |title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> A culture has developed around Sakawa which has influenced music and clothing brands. Movies depicting the lifestyle have become popular, a movement lead by Ghanaian filmaker [[Socrate Safo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Morton |title=The Sakawa Boys: Inside the Bizarre Criminal World of Ghana\u2019s Cyber-Juju Email Scam Gangs |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/4xx393/the-sakawa-boys-inside-the-bizarre-criminal-world-of-ghanas-cyber-juju-email-scam-gangs |website=Vice |language=en |date=5 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Crime in Ghana]]\n*[[Nigerian scam]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/4xx393/the-sakawa-boys-inside-the-bizarre-criminal-world-of-ghanas-cyber-juju-email-scam-gangs The Sakawa Boys], a documentary about the phenomenon.\n*[http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/off-topic/a-look-at-the-real-social-engineers/ A Look at the Real African Social Engineers], an article on Sakawa culture.\n*[http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/security-awareness/the-anatomy-of-a-scam/ The Anatomy Of a Sakawa Scam], an article detailing sakawa type frauds.\n\n[[Category:Crime in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Internet fraud]]\n[[Category:African witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Crimes involving Satanism or the occult]]\n\n{{ghana-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jwale2", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakawa"}
{"title_page": "Liam Bekric", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Liam Bekric\n| image          = XXXX15 - Liam Bekric - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| fullname       = Liam James Bekric\n| nicknames      = Bed-Quick\n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| classification = S13, SB13, SM13\n| strokes        = Breaststroke\n| club           = Norwood Swimming Club\n| coach          = Shaun Curtis\n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2001|1|7|df=yes}} \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| medaltemplates = \n<!-- don't include medal templates unless there is a medal \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[paralympic swimming]]}}\n-->\n}}\n\n'''Liam Bekric''' (born 7 January 2001) is an Australian Paralympic swimmer with a vision impairment. Bekric represented Australia for the first time at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rio Paralympic swim team led by record breakers Ellie Cole, Tiffany Thomas Kane and Jeremy McClure |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-14/world-record-breakers-head-australian-paralympic-swim-team/7325320 |accessdate=30 August 2016 |work=ANC News |date=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBekric was born on 7 January 2001 in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], to parents Dragan and Tracy, and is brother to Josh, Riley and Darcy.<ref>{{cite book |title=Annual Report  2012/2013 - Royal Blind Society |url=http://www.rsb.org.au/sites/all/themes/rsb/pdf/RSB-Annual-Report-2012-13_(web).pdf |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=apc/><ref name=\"ipc\">{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=1466604&sportid=514 |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> He was born with [[retinitis pigmentosa]], a hereditary, degenerative eye condition that results in tunnel vision and can lead to blindness.<ref name=messenger/><ref name=\"apc\">{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/liam-bekric/ |website=Australian Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> It was detected when he was six years old. Bekric's great-uncle and father have the same condition.<ref name=messenger/>  In 2016 he was a student at [[Underdale High School]] in [[Adelaide]].<ref name=\"underdale\">{{cite web |title=Individual Achievements |url= http://www.underdale.sa.edu.au/images/Newsletters/2015/Newsletter-Dec-15th-2015.pdf |website=Underdale High School Newsletter |date= 9 December 2015 |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=apc/> He was an ambassador for Variety and the Royal Society for the Blind \u2013 Dark to Light walk.<ref name=apc/> After swimming, he would like to be a schoolteacher.<ref name=apc/>\n\n==Swimming==\nBekric competes in the [[S13 (classification)|S13]] classification for swimmers with vision impairment.<ref name=apc/> He started swimming lessons at three years old. He is a member of the Norwood Swimming Club.<ref name=apc/> He began swimming competitively in 2011 and made his breakthrough in 2014.<ref name=apc/>  In 2013, Bekric slipped while playing soccer and fractured his wrist. The injury kept him out of the pool for a month before he got a waterproof cast and continued training.<ref name=apc/> He competed at the [[Australian Swimming Championships]] for the first time in 2014.<ref name=apc/> In November 2014, he won a bronze medal in the multi-class 50m breaststroke at the Australian Short Course Championships.<ref name=\"messenger\">{{cite news |last1=Turner|first1=Matt |title=Visually impaired swimmer Liam Bekric is youngest medallist at Australian Short Course Championships |url= http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/messenger/sport/visually-impaired-swimmer-liam-bekric-is-youngest-medallist-at-australian-short-course-championships/news-story/aef142dfc8bc13a24fb90d2712342782 |accessdate=30 August 2016 |work=Messenger Community News |date=19 November 2014}}</ref> Bekric was just 13 years old, the youngest competitor at the event, racing competitors 10 years his senior. He was just 0.1 of a second off getting silver.\n\nAt the 2015 Australian Swimming Championships, he made the final in the Men's 50m breaststrokes finishing fifth and the Men's 50m butterfly finishing seventh.<ref name=apc/> Bekric won gold at the 2015 Australian Age Championships, in the 50m freestyle and breaststroke \u2013 defending both his titles from 2014. He also took silver in the Men's 50m and 100m butterfly, bronze in the Men's 200m individual medley. He represented Australia for the first time at the 2015 Japanese National Championships and won gold medals in the Men's 50 & 100m breaststroke and Men's 50m freestyle.<ref name=underdale/>\n\nAs of 2016, he is a [[South Australian Sports Institute]] scholarship holder.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 SASI Individual Athlete Program athletes announced |url=http://sasi.sa.gov.au/news/?a=249398|website=South Australian Sports Institute website |accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Rio Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympic Games]], Bekric finished fourth in the final of Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, but did not progress to the finals in the Men's 400m Freestyle S13, Men's 100m Backstroke S13 or Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/liam-bekric |website=Rio Paralympics Official Results |publisher=Rio Paralympics 2016 |accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he was inducted into Swimming South Australia Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=SwimmingSA Hall of Fame |url=https://sa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall_of_Fame_Images/SwimmingSA%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20-%20Website.pdf |website=Swimming South Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202024646/https://sa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall_of_Fame_Images/SwimmingSA%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20-%20Website.pdf |archivedate=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/liam-bekric/ Liam Bekric] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|id=liam-bekric|old_id=1466604}}\n* [https://www.myswimresults.com.au/DashBoard.aspx?ID=103476 Liam Bekric] at My Swim Results\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bekric, Liam}}\n[[Category:Male Paralympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from South Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:S13-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Liam Bekric\n| image          = XXXX15 - Liam Bekric - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| fullname       = Liam James Bekric\n| nicknames      = Bed-Quick\n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| classification = S13, SB13, SM13\n| strokes        = Breaststroke\n| club           = Norwood Swimming Club\n| coach          = Shaun Curtis\n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2001|1|7|df=yes}} \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| medaltemplates = \n<!-- don't include medal templates unless there is a medal \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[paralympic swimming]]}}\n-->\n}}\n\n'''Liam Bekric''' (born 7 January 2001) is an Australian Paralympic swimmer with a vision impairment. Bekric represented Australia for the first time at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rio Paralympic swim team led by record breakers Ellie Cole, Tiffany Thomas Kane and Jeremy McClure |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-14/world-record-breakers-head-australian-paralympic-swim-team/7325320 |accessdate=30 August 2016 |work=ANC News |date=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBekric was born on 7 January 2001 in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], to parents Dragan and Tracy, and is brother to Josh, Riley and Darcy.<ref>{{cite book |title=Annual Report  2012/2013 - Royal Blind Society |url=http://www.rsb.org.au/sites/all/themes/rsb/pdf/RSB-Annual-Report-2012-13_(web).pdf |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=apc/><ref name=\"ipc\">{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=1466604&sportid=514 |website=International Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> He was born with [[retinitis pigmentosa]], a hereditary, degenerative eye condition that results in tunnel vision and can lead to blindness.<ref name=messenger/><ref name=\"apc\">{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/liam-bekric/ |website=Australian Paralympic Committee website |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> It was detected when he was six years old. Bekric's great-uncle and father have the same condition.<ref name=messenger/>  In 2016 he was a student at [[Underdale High School]] in [[Adelaide]].<ref name=\"underdale\">{{cite web |title=Individual Achievements |url= http://www.underdale.sa.edu.au/images/Newsletters/2015/Newsletter-Dec-15th-2015.pdf |website=Underdale High School Newsletter |date= 9 December 2015 |accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=apc/> He was an ambassador for Variety and the Royal Society for the Blind \u2013 Dark to Light walk.<ref name=apc/> After swimming, he would like to be a schoolteacher.<ref name=apc/>\n\n==Swimming==\nBekric competes in the [[S13 (classification)|S13]] classification for swimmers with vision impairment.<ref name=apc/> He started swimming lessons at three years old. He is a member of the Norwood Swimming Club.<ref name=apc/> He began swimming competitively in 2011 and made his breakthrough in 2014.<ref name=apc/>  In 2013, Bekric slipped while playing soccer and fractured his wrist. The injury kept him out of the pool for a month before he got a waterproof cast and continued training.<ref name=apc/> He competed at the [[Australian Swimming Championships]] for the first time in 2014.<ref name=apc/> In November 2014, he won a bronze medal in the multi-class 50m breaststroke at the Australian Short Course Championships.<ref name=\"messenger\">{{cite news |last1=Turner|first1=Matt |title=Visually impaired swimmer Liam Bekric is youngest medallist at Australian Short Course Championships |url= http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/messenger/sport/visually-impaired-swimmer-liam-bekric-is-youngest-medallist-at-australian-short-course-championships/news-story/aef142dfc8bc13a24fb90d2712342782 |accessdate=30 August 2016 |work=Messenger Community News |date=19 November 2014}}</ref> Bekric was just 13 years old, the youngest competitor at the event, racing competitors 10 years his senior. He was just 0.1 of a second off getting silver.\n\nAt the 2015 Australian Swimming Championships, he made the final in the Men's 50m breaststrokes finishing fifth and the Men's 50m butterfly finishing seventh.<ref name=apc/> Bekric won gold at the 2015 Australian Age Championships, in the 50m freestyle and breaststroke \u2013 defending both his titles from 2014. He also took silver in the Men's 50m and 100m butterfly, bronze in the Men's 200m individual medley. He represented Australia for the first time at the 2015 Japanese National Championships and won gold medals in the Men's 50 & 100m breaststroke and Men's 50m freestyle.<ref name=underdale/>\n\nAs of 2016, he is a [[South Australian Sports Institute]] scholarship holder.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 SASI Individual Athlete Program athletes announced |url=http://sasi.sa.gov.au/news/?a=249398|website=South Australian Sports Institute website |accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Rio Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympic Games]], Bekric finished fourth in the final of Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, but did not progress to the finals in the Men's 400m Freestyle S13, Men's 100m Backstroke S13 or Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liam Bekric |url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/liam-bekric |website=Rio Paralympics Official Results |publisher=Rio Paralympics 2016 |accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he was inducted into Swimming South Australia Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=SwimmingSA Hall of Fame |url=https://sa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall_of_Fame_Images/SwimmingSA%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20-%20Website.pdf |website=Swimming South Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202024646/https://sa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall_of_Fame_Images/SwimmingSA%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20-%20Website.pdf |archivedate=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/liam-bekric/ Liam Bekric] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|1466604}}\n* [https://www.myswimresults.com.au/DashBoard.aspx?ID=103476 Liam Bekric] at My Swim Results\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bekric, Liam}}\n[[Category:Male Paralympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from South Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:S13-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liam_Bekric"}
{"title_page": "Steve Matteson", "text_new": "'''Steven R. Matteson''' (born 1965, [[Chicago, Illinois]]) is an American [[typeface]] designer whose work is included in several computer operating systems and embedded in game consoles, cell phones and other electronic devices.<ref name=\"Steve Matteson interview\">{{cite web|title=Steve Matteson interview|url=https://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201205.html|website=MyFonts|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> He is the designer of the Microsoft font family [[Segoe UI|Segoe]] included since [[Windows XP]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itmanagement.earthweb.com/columns/executive_tech/article.php/3601421 |title=Designer Says Vista Font is Original |first=Brian |last=Livingston|date=25 April 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302120256/http://itmanagement.earthweb.com/columns/executive_tech/article.php/3601421 |archivedate=2007-03-02}}</ref> of the [[droid (font)|Droid]] font collection used in the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile device platform,<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/pr/pr2007_11_12.html Ascender creates the new Droid font collection for Open Handset Alliance's Android platform<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and designed the brand and user-interface fonts used in both the original Microsoft [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] and the [[Xbox 360]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070829184241/http://www.desktopmag.com.au/news_articles.php?article_id=24&type=Featured%20Articles&period=200704 Desktop - Australian Design, Digital Culture, Melbourne, Australia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMatteson is a 1988 graduate of [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] where he studied [[typography]], [[design]] and printing. Upon graduation he spent two years learning [[font hinting]] technology while employed at laser-printer manufacturer QMS.\n\nIn 1990 Matteson began work at [[Monotype Corporation]] (later Agfa-Monotype) contributing to the creation of the [[Windows 3.1x]] core [[TrueType]] fonts: [[Arial]], [[Times New Roman]] and [[Courier New]].<ref>[http://www.myfonts.com/person/matteson/steve/ Steve Matteson : MyFonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMatteson produced fonts for the Agfa-Monotype library (such as [[Goudy Ornate]] and [[Gill Floriated Capitals]]) and directed custom-font design for companies including [[Agilent Technologies]],<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#Agilent Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]] and [[Microsoft]].<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#MS_Corp Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Matteson designed [[Andal\u00e9 Mono]] as a mono-spaced command line and coding font for [[Taligent]]. The font is now bundled with [[Mac OS X]] and was one of the original [[Core fonts for the Web]].\n\nMatteson directed custom type development for Agfa-Monotype until 2003. In 2004 he became a founding partner and Director of Type Design at [[Ascender Corporation]] in [[Elk Grove Village]], Illinois.<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/stevepage.html Steve Matteson<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Matteson designed the font family Convection for use in the branding and user-interface of Microsoft\u2019s [[Xbox 360]] game console. Matteson also designed the user-interface font used in Microsoft\u2019s [[Zune]] music player.<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#Zune Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2007 software maker [[Red Hat]] released the open-source [[Liberation fonts]] family designed by Matteson.<ref>[https://www.redhat.com/promo/fonts/ redhat.com |<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Also in 2007, Matteson designed the [[Droid (font)|Droid]] family of fonts included in the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile-phone platform supported by the [[Open Handset Alliance]].\n\n==Fonts designed by Steve Matteson==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Andal\u00e9 Mono]]\n*[[Andal\u00e9 Sans]]\n*Andy Bold\n*[[Croscore fonts|Arimo]]\n*Ascender Sans\n*Ascender Sans Bold\n*Ascender Serif\n*Ascender Serif Bold\n*Ayita\n*Ayita Bold\n*Binner Gothic\n*Blueprint\n*[[Cambria (typeface)|Cambria]]\n*[[Cambria (typeface)|Cambria Bold]]\n*Chicory\n*Convection\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Croscore fonts|Cousine]]\n*[[Curlz]]\n*Dujour\n*[[Droid (font)|Droid]]\n*Endurance Pro\n*Endurance Pro Black\n*Endurance Pro Light\n*Facade Condensed\n*Fineprint\n*Fineprint Swash One\n*Fineprint Swash Two\n*Goudy Ornate\n*Kootenay Pro\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Mono]]\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Sans]]\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Serif]]\n*Lindsey Pro\n*Massif Pro\n*Mayberry\n*Miramonte Pro\n*Miramonte Pro Bold\n*[[Noto fonts|Noto Sans for Latin]]<ref name=\"Noto FAQ\">{{cite web|title=Noto FAQ|url=https://www.google.com/get/noto/help/faq/|website=Google Noto Fonts|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Open Sans]]\n*[[Open Sans|Open Sans Condensed]]\n*Open Serif\n*Othello\n*Pescadero Pro\n*Pescadero Pro Bold\n*[[Segoe]]\n*Sports Three\n*Sports Two\n*[[Croscore fonts|Tinos]]\n{{col-4}}\n*Titanium\n*Truesdell\n*Truesdell Ornaments\n*Twentieth Century Poster Fonts\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matteson, Steve}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:American typographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Steven R. Matteson''' (born 1965, [[Chicago, Illinois]]) is an American [[typeface]] designer whose work is included in several computer operating systems and embedded in game consoles, cell phones and other electronic devices.<ref name=\"Steve Matteson interview\">{{cite web|title=Steve Matteson interview|url=https://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201205.html|website=MyFonts|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> He is the designer of the Microsoft font family [[Segoe UI|Segoe]] included since [[Windows XP]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itmanagement.earthweb.com/columns/executive_tech/article.php/3601421 |title=Designer Says Vista Font is Original |first=Brian |last=Livingston|date=25 April 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302120256/http://itmanagement.earthweb.com/columns/executive_tech/article.php/3601421 |archivedate=2007-03-02}}</ref> of the [[droid (font)|Droid]] font collection used in the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile device platform,<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/pr/pr2007_11_12.html Ascender creates the new Droid font collection for Open Handset Alliance's Android platform<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and designed the brand and user-interface fonts used in both the original Microsoft [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] and the [[Xbox 360]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070829184241/http://www.desktopmag.com.au/news_articles.php?article_id=24&type=Featured%20Articles&period=200704 Desktop - Australian Design, Digital Culture, Melbourne, Australia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMatteson is a 1988 graduate of the [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] where he studied [[typography]], [[design]] and printing. Upon graduation he spent two years learning [[font hinting]] technology while employed at laser-printer manufacturer QMS.\n\nIn 1990 Matteson began work at [[Monotype Corporation]] (later Agfa-Monotype) contributing to the creation of the [[Windows 3.1x]] core [[TrueType]] fonts: [[Arial]], [[Times New Roman]] and [[Courier New]].<ref>[http://www.myfonts.com/person/matteson/steve/ Steve Matteson : MyFonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMatteson produced fonts for the Agfa-Monotype library (such as [[Goudy Ornate]] and [[Gill Floriated Capitals]]) and directed custom-font design for companies including [[Agilent Technologies]],<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#Agilent Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]] and [[Microsoft]].<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#MS_Corp Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Matteson designed [[Andal\u00e9 Mono]] as a mono-spaced command line and coding font for [[Taligent]]. The font is now bundled with [[Mac OS X]] and was one of the original [[Core fonts for the Web]].\n\nMatteson directed custom type development for Agfa-Monotype until 2003. In 2004 he became a founding partner and Director of Type Design at [[Ascender Corporation]] in [[Elk Grove Village]], Illinois.<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/stevepage.html Steve Matteson<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Matteson designed the font family Convection for use in the branding and user-interface of Microsoft\u2019s [[Xbox 360]] game console. Matteson also designed the user-interface font used in Microsoft\u2019s [[Zune]] music player.<ref>[http://www.ascendercorp.com/portfolio_custom.html#Zune Ascender Portfolio - Custom Fonts<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2007 software maker [[Red Hat]] released the open-source [[Liberation fonts]] family designed by Matteson.<ref>[https://www.redhat.com/promo/fonts/ redhat.com |<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Also in 2007, Matteson designed the [[Droid (font)|Droid]] family of fonts included in the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile-phone platform supported by the [[Open Handset Alliance]].\n\n==Fonts designed by Steve Matteson==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Andal\u00e9 Mono]]\n*[[Andal\u00e9 Sans]]\n*Andy Bold\n*[[Croscore fonts|Arimo]]\n*Ascender Sans\n*Ascender Sans Bold\n*Ascender Serif\n*Ascender Serif Bold\n*Ayita\n*Ayita Bold\n*Binner Gothic\n*Blueprint\n*[[Cambria (typeface)|Cambria]]\n*[[Cambria (typeface)|Cambria Bold]]\n*Chicory\n*Convection\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Croscore fonts|Cousine]]\n*[[Curlz]]\n*Dujour\n*[[Droid (font)|Droid]]\n*Endurance Pro\n*Endurance Pro Black\n*Endurance Pro Light\n*Facade Condensed\n*Fineprint\n*Fineprint Swash One\n*Fineprint Swash Two\n*Goudy Ornate\n*Kootenay Pro\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Mono]]\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Sans]]\n{{col-4}}\n*[[Liberation fonts|Liberation Serif]]\n*Lindsey Pro\n*Massif Pro\n*Mayberry\n*Miramonte Pro\n*Miramonte Pro Bold\n*[[Noto fonts|Noto Sans for Latin]]<ref name=\"Noto FAQ\">{{cite web|title=Noto FAQ|url=https://www.google.com/get/noto/help/faq/|website=Google Noto Fonts|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Open Sans]]\n*[[Open Sans|Open Sans Condensed]]\n*Open Serif\n*Othello\n*Pescadero Pro\n*Pescadero Pro Bold\n*[[Segoe]]\n*Sports Three\n*Sports Two\n*[[Croscore fonts|Tinos]]\n{{col-4}}\n*Titanium\n*Truesdell\n*Truesdell Ornaments\n*Twentieth Century Poster Fonts\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matteson, Steve}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:American typographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Andrew.burch", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammatical edit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Matteson"}
{"title_page": "Henry Leavitt Ellsworth", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Henry Leavitt Ellsworth\n| image         = HenryLeavittEllsworth.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, first Commissioner of the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|U.S. Patent Office]], founder, [[United States Department of Agriculture]]\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1791|11|10}}. \n| birth_place   = [[Windsor, Connecticut]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1858|12|27|1791|11|10}} \n| death_place   = [[Fair Haven, Connecticut]]\n| nationality   = [[United States]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = First [[Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Henry Leavitt Ellsworth''' (November 10, 1791 &ndash; December 27, 1858) was a Yale-educated attorney who became the first Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office, where he encouraged innovation by inventors [[Samuel F.B. Morse]] and [[Samuel Colt]]. Ellsworth also served as the second president of the [[Aetna|Aetna Insurance Company]], and was a major donor to [[Yale College]],<ref>Among the gifts and bequests made by Ellsworth to Yale was the Ellsworth Fund, which paid the tuition of [[Yale College]] students intending to enter the ministry.[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1894/10/08/106836706.pdf]</ref> a commissioner to Indian tribes on the western frontier, and the founder of what became the [[United States Department of Agriculture]].\n\n==Early life==\nEllsworth was born in [[Windsor, Connecticut]], son of [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father]] and [[Chief Justice]] [[Oliver Ellsworth]] and Abigail [[Roger Wolcott (Connecticut)|Wolcott]]. Ellsworth graduated from [[Yale University]] in 1810, and studied law at [[Tapping Reeve]]'s [[Litchfield Law School]] in 1811.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oK5NAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA571&dq=charleston+south+carolina+st.+philips+church+frost#PPA309,M1 Biographical Sketches of the Graduates of Yale College, Franklin Bowditch Dexter, Yale University Press, New Haven, 1912]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org/lawschool/students.html |title=Litchfield Law School Students, Litchfield Historical Society, litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org |access-date=2008-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228171353/http://www.litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org/lawschool/students.html |archive-date=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On June 22, 1813, he married Nancy Allen Goodrich (daughter of [[Congressman]], Judge, [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]] [[Mayor]] and longtime [[Secretary]] of the [[Yale Corporation]] [[Elizur Goodrich]] and his wife Anne Willard Allen) with whom Ellsworth had three children, including son [[Henry W. Ellsworth]].\n\nLater in life, he had two subsequent wives, Marietta Mariana Bartlett and Catherine Smith. Ellsworth was named in part for his grandmother's family, the Leavitts of [[Suffield, Connecticut]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WLfMU4yd1FYC&pg=PA407&lpg=PA407&dq=the+history+of+the+descendants+of+john+dwight+jemima+leavitt&source=web&ots=I935FNZuXW&sig=Nx7sxkJaqgjruaLPW3xlYf1n1XY&hl=en#PPA406,M1 The History of the Descendants of John Dwight, of Dedham, Mass., Benjamin Woodbridge Dwight, New York, 1874]</ref><ref>A later family relation was Vermont attorney and photography pioneer [[Leavitt Hunt]], whose full name was Henry Leavitt Hunt, and who was similarly named for his mother's Suffield Leavitt forebears.</ref> After studying law under Judge Gould in [[Litchfield, Connecticut]], he settled first at Windsor and then at [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], where he remained for a decade.\n\n==Travels==\nIn 1811, when he was 19 years old and a freshly minted Yale graduate, Ellsworth undertook the first of several western trips during his lifetime. Ellsworth traveled by horseback to the [[Connecticut Western Reserve]] in present-day [[Ohio]] to investigate family lands in the region. Ellsworth's father Oliver Ellsworth had purchased over {{convert|41000|acre|km2}} in the Western Reserve, including most of present-day [[Cleveland]], joining with other prominent Connecticut men snapping up over three million acres (12,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) sold by the state of Connecticut.<ref>The New Connecticut (Ohio) towns of Ellsworth and Windsor were named after the family and its Connecticut home.</ref> (Among the eight original purchasers was a family relation, merchant [[Thaddeus Leavitt]] of Suffield.) Ellsworth wrote a small, uneven book about his experiences entitled ''A Tour to New Connecticut in 1811''. Ellsworth's mission was straightening out irregularities in land sales by the family agent.\n\nIt was an arduous trip. Along the way Ellsworth made note of attractive vistas, rowdy drunks, solicitous innkeepers and his disappointment in places of which he had heard, like Erie. The journey's rigors were relieved by a meeting with his old friend Margaret Dwight, daughter of Yale president [[Timothy Dwight IV]], who was visiting family in present-day [[Warren, Ohio]]. \"Here too\", wrote Ellsworth, \"I met with my good old friend Margaret Dwight, we sat down and passed a few hours in social chat.\" Dwight wrote her own account of her Western Reserve trip, ''A Journey to Ohio in 1810''.<ref>Margaret Dwight's manuscript was edited by Max Farrand and published in 1912 as Volume I of the Yale Historical Manuscripts series.</ref>\n\nOver twenty years later, in 1832, Ellsworth traveled west again, this time as U.S. Commissioner of Indian Tribes in [[Arkansas]] and [[Oklahoma]].<ref>Ellsworth wrote a book about this journey entitled ''Washington Irving on the Prairie: Or, A Narrative of a Tour of the Southwest in the Year 1832''.</ref> President [[Andrew Jackson]] appointed Ellsworth one of three commissioners to \"study the country, to mark the boundaries, to pacify the warring Indians and, in general to establish order and justice\" after Congress's passage of the 1830 [[Indian Removal Act]]. Ellsworth travelled to [[Fort Gibson]] to investigate the situation. (Some critics blame Ellsworth for being complicit in the subsequent removal of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] to [[Indian Territory]], present-day Oklahoma, particularly since Ellsworth's appointment and subsequent western trip followed the Indian Removal Act, Andrew Jackson's first significant act as President. Other historians note Ellsworth's sympathetic outlook towards the tribes.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Y0tqzVNiFasC&pg=PA218&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&lr=&ei=kib0SO64I4HEMpiywOsI&sig=ACfU3U0yM9Q5YlhTC0ngmGzJEpeMZtMhsg Fugitive Poses: Native American Indian Scenes of Absence and Presence, Gerald Robert Vizenor, University of Nebraska Press, 1998]</ref>\n[[Image:OliverEllsworthWindsorCT.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Oliver Ellsworth Homestead]], Windsor, Connecticut, birthplace of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, National Historic Landmark]]\nAlong the way, Ellsworth made stops in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], then traveled on to [[St. Louis, Missouri]], where he met with explorer [[William Clark (explorer)|William Clark]] and saw the recently captured Native American leader [[Black Hawk (chief)|Black Hawk]], chief of the [[Sauk and Fox]] tribe. Leavitt's mission was a complicated one: he was charged with trying to mediate between the conflicting claims of several Indian tribes, who were being forced into an ever-smaller area, in competition with newer immigrants and the interests of the [[Chouteau]] family, the powerful St. Louis magnates of the Midwestern fur trade.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CyyuR36PNr4C&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+trail+of+tears&source=web&ots=v6drOD-jS2&sig=a8uQvAc2G3cS5yVmAE1h-CIWJkI&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result Aristocratic Encounters: European Travelers and North American Indians, Harry Liebersohn, Cambridge University Press, 1998]</ref>\n\nEllsworth was accompanied on the expedition by three companions: author [[Washington Irving]], who recorded his impressions in ''A Tour on the Prairies''; [[Charles La Trobe]], an [[Englishman]], [[mountaineer]] and [[travel writer]]  who later served in the [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|British diplomatic corps]] in the [[West Indies]] and [[Australia]]; and [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[Count]] Albert Pourtales.<ref>[http://digital.library.okstate.edu/Chronicles/v040/v040p355.pdf The Journal of the Union Mission, Hope Holway, [[University of Oklahoma]]]</ref>\n\nWashington Irving wrote of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, \"this worthy leader of our little band\": \"He was a native of one of the towns of Connecticut, a man in whom a course of legal practice and political life had not been able to vitiate an innate simplicity and benevolence of heart. The greater part of his days had been passed in the bosom of his family and the society of deacons, elders, and statesmen, on the peaceful banks of the Connecticut; when suddenly he had been called to mount his steed, shoulder his rifle and mingle among stark hunters, backwoodsmen, and naked savages, on the trackless wilds of the Far West.\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=a04VAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22a+tour+on+the+prairies%22+washington+irving&ei=vObwSNHyCJqktAOL99Fy#PPA2,M1 A Tour on the Prairies, Washington Irving, Henry G. Bohn, London, 1850]</ref>\n\n==Patent Office==\nIn 1835, Ellsworth was elected mayor of Hartford, Connecticut, but had served only a month when he was appointed the first Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office, an office he held for ten years, from 1835 until 1845. His twin brother [[William W. Ellsworth]] was [[Governor of Connecticut]] from 1838 to 1842, and served as a U.S. Congressman from Connecticut as well. William Wolcott Ellsworth was married to the daughter of [[Noah Webster]], the publisher of the eponymous dictionaries.\n\nWhen he arrived at the Patent Office, Ellsworth found one third of the floor-space in his office occupied by over 60 models of inventions; he moved them to a separate room. He also found that no list of patent applicants had ever been drawn up, a deficiency he soon corrected.\n[[File:500 Farmers Wanted.jpg|thumb|right|175px|[[Broadside (printing)|Broadside]] advertising sale by Ellsworth of parcels of his western lands, [[Lafayette, Indiana]], 1847]]\nActing as Patent Commissioner, Ellsworth made a decision that profoundly affected the future of Hartford and Connecticut. The young Samuel Colt was struggling to establish a firm to manufacture his new revolver. Ellsworth became interested in Colt's invention, and in 1836 made the decision to issue Colt U.S. Patent No. 138. On the basis of Ellsworth's decision, Colt was able to raise some $200,000 from investors to incorporate the Patent Arms Manufacturing Company of [[Paterson, New Jersey]], the forerunner of the mighty [[Colt's Manufacturing Company|Colt arms]] manufacturing empire.<ref>[http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1968/4/1968_4_4.shtml Gunmaker to the World, Ellsavorth S. Grant, American Heritage Magazine, June 1968, americanheritage.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905040115/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1968/4/1968_4_4.shtml |date=2008-09-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn today's world Ellsworth would be described as an early technology adapter. He became so interested, for instance, in a new-fangled invention by [[Samuel Morse]] called the telegraph that Ellsworth petitioned Congress for a $30,000 grant to test the possibilities of the technology.<ref>[http://patentmodelassociation.com/story.html The Story of the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, patentmodelassociation.com]</ref>\n\nFrom Ellsworth's exposure to the [[Western United States|West]] and knowledge of inventions, he prophesied late in life that the lands of the West would be cultivated by means of steam plows. This prophecy was introduced in the probate of his will in an attempt to prove that he was of unsound mind.\n\nEllsworth was proven correct, of course, and his interest in agriculture during his time as Patent Commissioner induced Congress in 1839 to appropriate the first monies for farming, which were used to collect seeds from foreign countries and distribute them through the United States post office, as Ellsworth had urged. By 1845 Ellsworth's patent office was performing the functions of a full-fledged agricultural bureau. For this accomplishment Ellsworth earned the sobriquet \"Father of the United States Department of Agriculture.\"\n\nA comment by Ellsworth about the increased workload at the patent office, taken out of context and embellished, was apparently the source of an [[urban legend]] that a patent office official ([[Charles H. Duell]] in some versions) claimed that everything which could be invented had already been invented.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2843/is_3_27/ai_100755224 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903213912/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2843/is_3_27/ai_100755224 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2004-09-03 | title=A Patently False Patent Myth still | journal=Skeptical Inquirer | date=May\u2013June 2003 | author=Samuel Sass | format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AA+Patently+False+Patent+Myth+still&as_publication=Skeptical+Inquirer&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}}</ref> In his 1843 report to Congress, Ellsworth stated: \"The advancement of the arts, from year to year, taxes our credulity and seems to presage the arrival of that period when human improvement must end.\" The report then lists a record number of patents, implying his comment was intended to be humorous.<ref>Samuel Sass, \"A Patently False Patent Myth\", ''The Skeptical Inquirer'', Spring 1989, vol. 13, pp. 3110-313.</ref>\n\nFollowing Ellsworth's stint in the Patent Office, he settled in Lafayette, Indiana, acting as an agent for purchase and settlement of public land, but in 1857 he returned to Connecticut. Ellsworth later served as an early president of the Aetna Insurance Company. He was an early benefactor of [[Yale College]], donating some $700,000 to his alma mater, as well as title to the Ellsworth lands in the former [[Western Reserve]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PfYLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA295&lpg=PA295&dq=aetna+%22henry+l.+ellsworth%22&source=web&ots=SZzDlbYW3z&sig=bmAexlF3MqsctDaDcyd5JxHNQBo&hl=en The Connecticut Magazine: An Illustrated Monthly, William Farrand Felch, Vol. I, January, 1895, Hartford]</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Morse Telegraph 1837.jpg|thumb|left|The Morse Telegraph, one of many inventions championed by Henry Leavitt Ellsworth]]\n\nEllsworth died, aged 67, on December 27, 1858 in [[Fair Haven (New Haven)|Fair Haven, Connecticut]]. Following his death, Ellsworth's papers were discovered among the family papers of the Goodrich family. Ellsworth was a Yale classmate of [[Chauncey Allen Goodrich]],<ref>Chauncey Allen Goodrich was also the brother-in-law of William Wolcott Ellsworth, Henry Leavitt's brother. Goodrich and Ellsworth had both married daughters of dictionary publisher Noah Webster.</ref> whose sister Nancy Henry Leavitt Ellsworth married. The journal of Ellsworth's first trip to New Connecticut came to the [[Yale University Library]] as part of the Goodrich Family Collection. The former patent commissioner's papers  today make up the Henry Leavitt Ellsworth Papers at Yale's Sterling Library.\nAnnie Goodrich Ellsworth, only daughter of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, married the publisher Roswell Smith, who with his partner [[Josiah Gilbert Holland]] founded, in partnership with the publishing house [[Charles Scribner I|Charles Scribner & Co.]], ''[[Scribner's Magazine|Scribner's Monthly]]'' and ''[[St. Nicholas Magazine|St. Nicholas]]'' magazines.<ref>Oliver Ellsworth, the son of William W. Ellsworth, twin brother of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, married Caroline Cleveland Smith, whose first cousin was Roswell Smith, who married Anna G. Leavitt, Oliver's first cousin.  Oliver Ellsworth's son William Webster Ellsworth went into the Century Company publishing business with Roswell Smith, where he helped publish the Century Dictionary.[https://books.google.com/books?id=uIRCsrMwhroC&pg=PA16&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=wiH0SJTuEZeUM5mRjNgI&sig=ACfU3U1CIcUGIWtklRbYPIgIXwyMLeWzVA]</ref> Later Smith founded the publishing house [[The Century Company]], and assumed sole ownership of both magazines. He changed the name of  ''Scribner's Monthly'' to ''The Century''. His wife, the former Anna G. Ellsworth, dictated the inaugural message on Samuel F. B. Morse's new telegraph system. \"What hath God wrought\" read the message, suggested by her mother, the wife of Morse's great champion Henry Leavitt Ellsworth.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_e0UAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT441&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=tx70SJ-HF4nIMszCmdwI The Twentieth Century Biographical Dictionary of Notable Americans, Rossiter Johnson (ed.), Vol. IX, The Biographical Society, Boston, 1904]</ref><ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?mcc:1:./temp/~ammem_Np3W::@@@mdb=mcc,gottscho,detr,nfor,wpa,aap,cwar,bbpix,cowellbib,calbkbib,consrvbib,bdsbib,dag,fsaall,gmd,pan,vv,presp,varstg,suffrg,nawbib,horyd,wtc,toddbib,mgw,ncr,ngp,musdibib,hlaw,papr,lhbumbib,rbpebib,lbcoll,alad,hh,aaodyssey,magbell,bbc,dcm,raelbib,runyon,dukesm,lomaxbib,mtj,gottlieb,aep,qlt,coolbib,fpnas,aasm,denn,relpet,amss,aaeo,mff,afc911bib,mjm,mnwp,rbcmillerbib,molden,ww2map,mfdipbib,afcnyebib,klpmap,hawp,omhbib,rbaapcbib,mal,ncpsbib,ncpm,lhbprbib,ftvbib,afcreed,aipn,cwband,flwpabib,wpapos,cmns,psbib,pin,coplandbib,cola,tccc,curt,mharendt,lhbcbbib,eaa,haybib,mesnbib,fine,cwnyhs,svybib,mmorse,afcwwgbib,mymhiwebib,uncall,afcwip,mtaft,manz,llstbib,fawbib,berl,fmuever,cdn,upboverbib,mussm,cic,afcpearl,awh,awhbib,sgp,wright,lhbtnbib,afcesnbib,hurstonbib,mreynoldsbib,spaldingbib,sgproto,scsmbib,afccalbib First Telegraph Message, 24 May 1844, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.]</ref> The daughter of Roswell Smith and Anna G. Leavitt married the American artist landscape painter [[George Inness, Jr.]] <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YAgWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA23&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=8CP0SNPRJpOqMqWM9cAL A Memorial of the Opening of the Ellsworth Homestead at Windsor, Connecticut, Connecticut Daughters of the American Revolution, Tuttle, Morehouse & Taylor Co., 1903]</ref>\n[[File:The First Telegraph.jpg|thumb|Text of the first telegraph message sent by [[Samuel F. B. Morse]]. Presented to Miss Annie G. Ellsworth, daughter of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth. Annie's ink tracing over Morse's pencilled letters. Gift to [[Library of Congress]] by Mrs. George Inness, daughter of Annie Ellsworth]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Patent Office 1877 fire]]\n*[[Patent Office 1836 fire]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | title =Henry L. Ellsworth Circular, 1837 | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =1993-05-21 | url =http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/henry-l-ellsworth-circular-1837.pdf | accessdate =2012-11-05}}\n*[http://aghalloffame.com/hall/ellsworth.aspx Henry Leavitt Ellsworth], National Agricultural Hall of Fame\n*[http://mssa.library.yale.edu/findaids/stream.php?xmlfile=mssa.ms.0196.xml Guide to the Henry Leavitt Ellsworth Papers], Yale University Library\n*[http://images.lib.uconn.edu/cdm-cho/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/cho&CISOPTR=166&CISOBOX=1&REC=1 500 Farmers Wanted, Advertisement for Land Sale by Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, Lafayette, Indiana, April 29, 1847], Connecticut History Online\n*[http://digitalgallery.nypl.org/nypldigital/dgkeysearchdetail.cfm?trg=1&strucID=575998&imageID=1228617&total=18&num=0&word=leavitt&s=1&notword=&d=&c=&f=&k=0&lWord=&lField=&sScope=&sLevel=&sLabel=&imgs=20&pos=1&e=w Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, of Connecticut], New York Public Library Digital Gallery\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''A Tour to New Connecticut in 1811: The Narrative of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth'', Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, Phillip R. Shriver (ed.), Volume I of the Western Reserve History Studies Series, The Western Reserve Historical Society, Cleveland, 1985\n*  ''Washington Irving on the Prairie: Or, A Narrative of a Tour of the Southwest in the Year 1832'', Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, (edited by [[Stanley Thomas Williams]] and Barbara Damon Simison), American Book Company, 1937\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=bZwZAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=henry+leavitt+ellsworth&source=bl&ots=nvA4-7uLHE&sig=IRHdtk43pWbUfvR7d_3GQi2cW20&hl=en&ei=5ZxhS-LhF4GSsgOMucHFCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CCsQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false A Letter on the Cultivation of the Prairies, Hon. H. L. Ellsworth, Published by S. Augustus Mitchell, Philadelphia, 1837]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=P-pIAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22&source=bl&ots=lqwMmMiBcV&sig=sHxnWAFMw3MITEArDxhD-gtiBoE&hl=en&ei=_ET7S9faH5PENqSe_OMB&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Improvements in Agriculture, Arts, & C. of the United States, Hon. Henry L. Ellsworth, Greeley & McElrath, New York, 1843]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellsworth, Henry Leavitt}}\n[[Category:1791 births]]\n[[Category:1858 deaths]]\n[[Category:American pioneers]]\n[[Category:Lafayette, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Farmers from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Leavitt family]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in insurance]]\n[[Category:People from Windsor, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Benefactors of Yale University]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Connecticut lawyers]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:American travel writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:United States Superintendents of Patents]]\n[[Category:United States Commissioners of Patents]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Henry Leavitt Ellsworth\n| image         = HenryLeavittEllsworth.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, first Commissioner of the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|U.S. Patent Office]], founder, [[United States Department of Agriculture]]\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1791|11|10}}. \n| birth_place   = [[Windsor, Connecticut]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1858|12|27|1791|11|10}} \n| death_place   = [[Fair Haven, Connecticut]]\n| nationality   = [[United States]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Attorney]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = First [[Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Henry Leavitt Ellsworth''' (November 10, 1791 &ndash; December 27, 1858) was a Yale-educated attorney who became the first Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office, where he encouraged innovation by inventors [[Samuel F.B. Morse]] and [[Samuel Colt]]. Ellsworth also served as the second president of the [[Aetna|Aetna Insurance Company]], and was a major donor to [[Yale College]],<ref>Among the gifts and bequests made by Ellsworth to Yale was the Ellsworth Fund, which paid the tuition of [[Yale College]] students intending to enter the ministry.[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1894/10/08/106836706.pdf]</ref> a commissioner to Indian tribes on the western frontier, and the founder of what became the [[United States Department of Agriculture]].\n\n==Early life==\nEllsworth was born in [[Windsor, Connecticut]], son of [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father]] and [[Chief Justice]] [[Oliver Ellsworth]] and Abigail [[Roger Wolcott (Connecticut)|Wolcott]]. Ellsworth graduated from [[Yale University]] in 1810, and studied law at [[Tapping Reeve]]'s [[Litchfield Law School]] in 1811.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oK5NAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA571&dq=charleston+south+carolina+st.+philips+church+frost#PPA309,M1 Biographical Sketches of the Graduates of Yale College, Franklin Bowditch Dexter, Yale University Press, New Haven, 1912]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org/lawschool/students.html |title=Litchfield Law School Students, Litchfield Historical Society, litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org |access-date=2008-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228171353/http://www.litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org/lawschool/students.html |archive-date=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On June 22, 1813, he married Nancy Allen Goodrich (daughter of [[Congressman]], Judge, [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]] [[Mayor]] and longtime [[Secretary]] of the [[Yale Corporation]] [[Elizur Goodrich]] and his wife Anne Willard Allen) with whom Ellsworth had three children, including son [[Henry W. Ellsworth]].\n\nLater in life, he had two subsequent wives, Marietta Mariana Bartlett and Catherine Smith. Ellsworth was named in part for his grandmother's family, the Leavitts of [[Suffield, Connecticut]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WLfMU4yd1FYC&pg=PA407&lpg=PA407&dq=the+history+of+the+descendants+of+john+dwight+jemima+leavitt&source=web&ots=I935FNZuXW&sig=Nx7sxkJaqgjruaLPW3xlYf1n1XY&hl=en#PPA406,M1 The History of the Descendants of John Dwight, of Dedham, Mass., Benjamin Woodbridge Dwight, New York, 1874]</ref><ref>A later family relation was Vermont attorney and photography pioneer [[Leavitt Hunt]], whose full name was Henry Leavitt Hunt, and who was similarly named for his mother's Suffield Leavitt forebears.</ref> After studying law under Judge Gould in [[Litchfield, Connecticut]], he settled first at Windsor and then at [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], where he remained for a decade.\n\n==Travels==\nIn 1811, when he was 19 years old and a freshly minted Yale graduate, Ellsworth undertook the first of several western trips during his lifetime. Ellsworth traveled by horseback to the [[Connecticut Western Reserve]] in present-day [[Ohio]] to investigate family lands in the region. Ellsworth's father Oliver Ellsworth had purchased over {{convert|41000|acre|km2}} in the Western Reserve, including most of present-day [[Cleveland]], joining with other prominent Connecticut men snapping up over three million acres (12,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) sold by the state of Connecticut.<ref>The New Connecticut (Ohio) towns of Ellsworth and Windsor were named after the family and its Connecticut home.</ref> (Among the eight original purchasers was a family relation, merchant [[Thaddeus Leavitt]] of Suffield.) Ellsworth wrote a small, uneven book about his experiences entitled ''A Tour to New Connecticut in 1811''. Ellsworth's mission was straightening out irregularities in land sales by the family agent.\n\nIt was an arduous trip. Along the way Ellsworth made note of attractive vistas, rowdy drunks, solicitous innkeepers and his disappointment in places of which he had heard, like Erie. The journey's rigors were relieved by a meeting with his old friend Margaret Dwight, daughter of Yale president [[Timothy Dwight IV]], who was visiting family in present-day [[Warren, Ohio]]. \"Here too\", wrote Ellsworth, \"I met with my good old friend Margaret Dwight, we sat down and passed a few hours in social chat.\" Dwight wrote her own account of her Western Reserve trip, ''A Journey to Ohio in 1810''.<ref>Margaret Dwight's manuscript was edited by Max Farrand and published in 1912 as Volume I of the Yale Historical Manuscripts series.</ref>\n\nOver twenty years later, in 1832, Ellsworth traveled west again, this time as U.S. Commissioner of Indian Tribes in [[Arkansas]] and [[Oklahoma]].<ref>Ellsworth wrote a book about this journey entitled ''Washington Irving on the Prairie: Or, A Narrative of a Tour of the Southwest in the Year 1832''.</ref> President [[Andrew Jackson]] appointed Ellsworth one of three commissioners to \"study the country, to mark the boundaries, to pacify the warring Indians and, in general to establish order and justice\" after Congress's passage of the 1830 [[Indian Removal Act]]. Ellsworth travelled to [[Fort Gibson]] to investigate the situation. (Some critics blame Ellsworth for being complicit in the subsequent removal of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] to [[Indian Territory]], present-day Oklahoma, particularly since Ellsworth's appointment and subsequent western trip followed the Indian Removal Act, Andrew Jackson's first significant act as President. Other historians note Ellsworth's sympathetic outlook towards the tribes.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Y0tqzVNiFasC&pg=PA218&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&lr=&ei=kib0SO64I4HEMpiywOsI&sig=ACfU3U0yM9Q5YlhTC0ngmGzJEpeMZtMhsg Fugitive Poses: Native American Indian Scenes of Absence and Presence, Gerald Robert Vizenor, University of Nebraska Press, 1998]</ref>\n[[Image:OliverEllsworthWindsorCT.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Oliver Ellsworth Homestead]], Windsor, Connecticut, birthplace of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, National Historic Landmark]]\nAlong the way, Ellsworth made stops in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], then traveled on to [[St. Louis, Missouri]], where he met with explorer [[William Clark (explorer)|William Clark]] and saw the recently captured Native American leader [[Black Hawk (chief)|Black Hawk]], chief of the [[Sauk and Fox]] tribe. Leavitt's mission was a complicated one: he was charged with trying to mediate between the conflicting claims of several Indian tribes, who were being forced into an ever-smaller area, in competition with newer immigrants and the interests of the [[Chouteau]] family, the powerful St. Louis magnates of the Midwestern fur trade.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CyyuR36PNr4C&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+trail+of+tears&source=web&ots=v6drOD-jS2&sig=a8uQvAc2G3cS5yVmAE1h-CIWJkI&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result Aristocratic Encounters: European Travelers and North American Indians, Harry Liebersohn, Cambridge University Press, 1998]</ref>\n\nEllsworth was accompanied on the expedition by three companions: author [[Washington Irving]], who recorded his impressions in ''A Tour on the Prairies''; [[Charles La Trobe]], an [[Englishman]], [[mountaineer]] and [[travel writer]]  who later served in the [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|British diplomatic corps]] in the [[West Indies]] and [[Australia]]; and [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[Count]] Albert Pourtales.<ref>[http://digital.library.okstate.edu/Chronicles/v040/v040p355.pdf The Journal of the Union Mission, Hope Holway, [[University of Oklahoma]]]</ref>\n\nWashington Irving wrote of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, \"this worthy leader of our little band\": \"He was a native of one of the towns of Connecticut, a man in whom a course of legal practice and political life had not been able to vitiate an innate simplicity and benevolence of heart. The greater part of his days had been passed in the bosom of his family and the society of deacons, elders, and statesmen, on the peaceful banks of the Connecticut; when suddenly he had been called to mount his steed, shoulder his rifle and mingle among stark hunters, backwoodsmen, and naked savages, on the trackless wilds of the Far West.\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=a04VAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22a+tour+on+the+prairies%22+washington+irving&ei=vObwSNHyCJqktAOL99Fy#PPA2,M1 A Tour on the Prairies, Washington Irving, Henry G. Bohn, London, 1850]</ref>\n\n==Patent Office==\nIn 1835, Ellsworth was elected mayor of Hartford, Connecticut, but had served only a month when he was appointed the first Commissioner of the U.S. Patent Office, an office he held for ten years, from 1835 until 1845. His twin brother [[William W. Ellsworth]] was [[Governor of Connecticut]] from 1838 to 1842, and served as a U.S. Congressman from Connecticut as well. William Wolcott Ellsworth was married to the daughter of [[Noah Webster]], the publisher of the eponymous dictionaries.\n\nWhen he arrived at the Patent Office, Ellsworth found one third of the floor-space in his office occupied by over 60 models of inventions; he moved them to a separate room. He also found that no list of patent applicants had ever been drawn up, a deficiency he soon corrected.\n[[File:500 Farmers Wanted.jpg|thumb|right|175px|[[Broadside (printing)|Broadside]] advertising sale by Ellsworth of parcels of his western lands, [[Lafayette, Indiana]], 1847]]\nActing as Patent Commissioner, Ellsworth made a decision that profoundly affected the future of Hartford and Connecticut. The young Samuel Colt was struggling to establish a firm to manufacture his new revolver. Ellsworth became interested in Colt's invention, and in 1836 made the decision to issue Colt U.S. Patent No. 138. On the basis of Ellsworth's decision, Colt was able to raise some $200,000 from investors to incorporate the Patent Arms Manufacturing Company of [[Paterson, New Jersey]], the forerunner of the mighty [[Colt's Manufacturing Company|Colt arms]] manufacturing empire.<ref>[http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1968/4/1968_4_4.shtml Gunmaker to the World, Ellsavorth S. Grant, American Heritage Magazine, June 1968, americanheritage.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905040115/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1968/4/1968_4_4.shtml |date=2008-09-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn today's world Ellsworth would be described as an early technology adapter. He became so interested, for instance, in a new-fangled invention by [[Samuel Morse]] called the telegraph that Ellsworth petitioned Congress for a $30,000 grant to test the possibilities of the technology.<ref>[http://patentmodelassociation.com/story.html The Story of the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, patentmodelassociation.com]</ref>\n\nFrom Ellsworth's exposure to the [[Western United States|West]] and knowledge of inventions, he prophesied late in life that the lands of the West would be cultivated by means of steam plows. This prophecy was introduced in the probate of his will in an attempt to prove that he was of unsound mind.\n\nEllsworth was proven correct, of course, and his interest in agriculture during his time as Patent Commissioner induced Congress in 1839 to appropriate the first monies for farming, which were used to collect seeds from foreign countries and distribute them through the United States post office, as Ellsworth had urged. By 1845 Ellsworth's patent office was performing the functions of a full-fledged agricultural bureau. For this accomplishment Ellsworth earned the sobriquet \"Father of the United States Department of Agriculture.\"\n\nA comment by Ellsworth about the increased workload at the patent office, taken out of context and embellished, was apparently the source of an [[urban legend]] that a patent office official ([[Charles H. Duell]] in some versions) claimed that everything which could be invented had already been invented.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2843/is_3_27/ai_100755224 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903213912/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2843/is_3_27/ai_100755224 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2004-09-03 | title=A Patently False Patent Myth still | journal=Skeptical Inquirer | date=May\u2013June 2003 | author=Samuel Sass | format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AA+Patently+False+Patent+Myth+still&as_publication=Skeptical+Inquirer&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}}</ref> In his 1843 report to Congress, Ellsworth stated: \"The advancement of the arts, from year to year, taxes our credulity and seems to presage the arrival of that period when human improvement must end.\" The report then lists a record number of patents, implying his comment was intended to be humorous.<ref>Samuel Sass, \"A Patently False Patent Myth\", ''The Skeptical Inquirer'', Spring 1989, vol. 13, pp. 3110-313.</ref>\n\nFollowing Ellsworth's stint in the Patent Office, he settled in Lafayette, Indiana, acting as an agent for purchase and settlement of public land, but in 1857 he returned to Connecticut. Ellsworth later served as an early president of the Aetna Insurance Company. He was an early benefactor of [[Yale College]], donating some $700,000 to his alma mater, as well as title to the Ellsworth lands in the former [[Western Reserve]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PfYLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA295&lpg=PA295&dq=aetna+%22henry+l.+ellsworth%22&source=web&ots=SZzDlbYW3z&sig=bmAexlF3MqsctDaDcyd5JxHNQBo&hl=en The Connecticut Magazine: An Illustrated Monthly, William Farrand Felch, Vol. I, January, 1895, Hartford]</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Morse Telegraph 1837.jpg|thumb|left|The Morse Telegraph, one of many inventions championed by Henry Leavitt Ellsworth]]\n\nEllsworth died, aged 67, on December 27, 1858 in [[Fair Haven (New Haven)|Fair Haven, Connecticut]]. Following his death, Ellsworth's papers were discovered among the family papers of the Goodrich family. Ellsworth was a Yale classmate of [[Chauncey Allen Goodrich]],<ref>Chauncey Allen Goodrich was also the brother-in-law of William Wolcott Ellsworth, Henry Leavitt's brother. Goodrich and Ellsworth had both married daughters of dictionary publisher Noah Webster.</ref> whose sister Nancy Henry Leavitt Ellsworth married. The journal of Ellsworth's first trip to New Connecticut came to the [[Yale University Library]] as part of the Goodrich Family Collection. The former patent commissioner's papers  today make up the Henry Leavitt Ellsworth Papers at Yale's Sterling Library.\nAnnie Goodrich Ellsworth, only daughter of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, married the publisher Roswell Smith, who with his partner [[Josiah Gilbert Holland]] founded, in partnership with the publishing house [[Charles Scribner I|Charles Scribner & Co.]], ''[[Scribner's Magazine|Scribner's Monthly]]'' and ''[[St. Nicholas Magazine|St. Nicholas]]'' magazines.<ref>Oliver Ellsworth, the son of William W. Ellsworth, twin brother of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, married Caroline Cleveland Smith, whose first cousin was Roswell Smith, who married Anna G. Leavitt, Oliver's first cousin.  Oliver Ellsworth's son William Webster Ellsworth went into the Century Company publishing business with Roswell Smith, where he helped publish the Century Dictionary.[https://books.google.com/books?id=uIRCsrMwhroC&pg=PA16&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=wiH0SJTuEZeUM5mRjNgI&sig=ACfU3U1CIcUGIWtklRbYPIgIXwyMLeWzVA]</ref> Later Smith founded the publishing house [[The Century Company]], and assumed sole ownership of both magazines. He changed the name of  ''Scribner's Monthly'' to ''The Century''. His wife, the former Anna G. Ellsworth, dictated the inaugural message on Samuel F. B. Morse's new telegraph system. \"What hath God wrought\" read the message, suggested by her mother, the wife of Morse's great champion Henry Leavitt Ellsworth.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_e0UAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT441&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=tx70SJ-HF4nIMszCmdwI The Twentieth Century Biographical Dictionary of Notable Americans, Rossiter Johnson (ed.), Vol. IX, The Biographical Society, Boston, 1904]</ref><ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?mcc:1:./temp/~ammem_Np3W::@@@mdb=mcc,gottscho,detr,nfor,wpa,aap,cwar,bbpix,cowellbib,calbkbib,consrvbib,bdsbib,dag,fsaall,gmd,pan,vv,presp,varstg,suffrg,nawbib,horyd,wtc,toddbib,mgw,ncr,ngp,musdibib,hlaw,papr,lhbumbib,rbpebib,lbcoll,alad,hh,aaodyssey,magbell,bbc,dcm,raelbib,runyon,dukesm,lomaxbib,mtj,gottlieb,aep,qlt,coolbib,fpnas,aasm,denn,relpet,amss,aaeo,mff,afc911bib,mjm,mnwp,rbcmillerbib,molden,ww2map,mfdipbib,afcnyebib,klpmap,hawp,omhbib,rbaapcbib,mal,ncpsbib,ncpm,lhbprbib,ftvbib,afcreed,aipn,cwband,flwpabib,wpapos,cmns,psbib,pin,coplandbib,cola,tccc,curt,mharendt,lhbcbbib,eaa,haybib,mesnbib,fine,cwnyhs,svybib,mmorse,afcwwgbib,mymhiwebib,uncall,afcwip,mtaft,manz,llstbib,fawbib,berl,fmuever,cdn,upboverbib,mussm,cic,afcpearl,awh,awhbib,sgp,wright,lhbtnbib,afcesnbib,hurstonbib,mreynoldsbib,spaldingbib,sgproto,scsmbib,afccalbib First Telegraph Message, 24 May 1844, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.]</ref> The daughter of Roswell Smith and Anna G. Leavitt married the American artist landscape painter [[George Inness, Jr.]] <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YAgWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA23&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22+smith&ei=8CP0SNPRJpOqMqWM9cAL A Memorial of the Opening of the Ellsworth Homestead at Windsor, Connecticut, Connecticut Daughters of the American Revolution, Tuttle, Morehouse & Taylor Co., 1903]</ref>\n[[File:The First Telegraph.jpg|thumb|Text of the first telegraph message sent by [[Samuel F. B. Morse]]. Presented to Miss Annie G. Ellsworth, daughter of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth. Annie's ink tracing over Morse's pencilled letters. Gift to [[Library of Congress]] by Mrs. George Inness, daughter of Annie Ellsworth]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Patent Office 1877 fire]]\n*[[Patent Office 1836 fire]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | title =Henry L. Ellsworth Circular, 1837 | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =1993-05-21 | url =http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/henry-l-ellsworth-circular-1837.pdf | accessdate =2012-11-05}}\n*[http://aghalloffame.com/hall/ellsworth.aspx Henry Leavitt Ellsworth], National Agricultural Hall of Fame\n*[http://mssa.library.yale.edu/findaids/stream.php?xmlfile=mssa.ms.0196.xml Guide to the Henry Leavitt Ellsworth Papers], Yale University Library\n*[http://images.lib.uconn.edu/cdm-cho/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/cho&CISOPTR=166&CISOBOX=1&REC=1 500 Farmers Wanted, Advertisement for Land Sale by Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, Lafayette, Indiana, April 29, 1847], Connecticut History Online\n*[http://digitalgallery.nypl.org/nypldigital/dgkeysearchdetail.cfm?trg=1&strucID=575998&imageID=1228617&total=18&num=0&word=leavitt&s=1&notword=&d=&c=&f=&k=0&lWord=&lField=&sScope=&sLevel=&sLabel=&imgs=20&pos=1&e=w Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, of Connecticut], New York Public Library Digital Gallery\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''A Tour to New Connecticut in 1811: The Narrative of Henry Leavitt Ellsworth'', Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, Phillip R. Shriver (ed.), Volume I of the Western Reserve History Studies Series, The Western Reserve Historical Society, Cleveland, 1985\n*  ''Washington Irving on the Prairie: Or, A Narrative of a Tour of the Southwest in the Year 1832'', Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, (edited by [[Stanley Thomas Williams]] and Barbara Damon Simison), American Book Company, 1937\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=bZwZAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=henry+leavitt+ellsworth&source=bl&ots=nvA4-7uLHE&sig=IRHdtk43pWbUfvR7d_3GQi2cW20&hl=en&ei=5ZxhS-LhF4GSsgOMucHFCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CCsQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false A Letter on the Cultivation of the Prairies, Hon. H. L. Ellsworth, Published by S. Augustus Mitchell, Philadelphia, 1837]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=P-pIAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22henry+leavitt+ellsworth%22&source=bl&ots=lqwMmMiBcV&sig=sHxnWAFMw3MITEArDxhD-gtiBoE&hl=en&ei=_ET7S9faH5PENqSe_OMB&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Improvements in Agriculture, Arts, & C. of the United States, Hon. Henry L. Ellsworth, Greeley & McElrath, New York, 1843]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{D